e aims. \n\n<strong><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://datapopalliance.org/people#bio-letouze\">Emmanuel Letouzé</a> is on the D4GX program committee.</strong>\n\nMore information about the event is available <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.bloomberg.com/D4GX\">here</a>.\n\n\";s:8:\"location\";s:66:\"Bloomberg, 731 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022, United States\";s:10:\"start_time\";i:1443429000;s:8:\"end_time\";i:1443461400;s:4:\"link\";s:116:\"https://www.google.com/calendar/event?eid=NHY2Zm9qanZkcmRwaDNlMmhmMmlqNnRqM2cgNmgzczUwa2IxaGZzcXVmZGx1c2pyZWJuNG9AZw\";s:8:\"day_type\";s:3:\"SPD\";}i:2;O:9:\"GCE_Event\":9:{s:4:\"feed\";r:3;s:2:\"id\";s:58:\"6kq3cp9kcgo3abb2c9hj2b9kc8r64b9pcosj4b9o6thjeeb664qm8p9gcc\";s:5:\"title\";s:53:\"Global Conference on Big Data for Official Statistics\";s:11:\"description\";s:398:\"<b>Organized by the National Bureau of Statistics of UAE, the United Nations Statistics Division and the Australian Bureau of Statistics</b>\n\nThe concept note and conference agenda are available <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://unstats.un.org/unsd/trade/events/2015/abudhabi/default.asp\">here</a>.\n\n<img src=\"http://unstats.un.org/unsd/trade/events/2015/abudhabi/abudhabi-banner.jpg\" width=\"100%\" />\";s:8:\"location\";s:14:\"Abu Dhabi, UAE\";s:10:\"start_time\";i:1445299200;s:8:\"end_time\";i:1445558400;s:4:\"link\";s:158:\"https://www.google.com/calendar/event?eid=NmtxM2NwOWtjZ28zYWJiMmM5aGoyYjlrYzhyNjRiOXBjb3NqNGI5bzZ0aGplZWI2NjRxbThwOWdjYyA2aDNzNTBrYjFoZnNxdWZkbHVzanJlYm40b0Bn\";s:8:\"day_type\";s:3:\"MWD\";}i:3;O:9:\"GCE_Event\":9:{s:4:\"feed\";r:3;s:2:\"id\";s:59:\"_60s36c1n60pj8b9i6gs46b9k6opjab9p6gs34b9l68qj6g9k6t1kah9h8g\";s:5:\"title\";s:89:\"Beyond Data Literacy: Reinventing Community Engagement and Empowerment in the Age of Data\";s:11:\"description\";s:1453:\"This White Paper Launch and Discussion Workshop is organized by Data-Pop Alliance and Internews, in partnership with PARIS21, the World Economic Forum (WEF), and the Sustainable Development Solutions Network (SDSN).  \n\n‘Data literacy’ has become one of the hottest policy concepts and priorities of the sustainable development agenda and the ‘Data Revolution’ discussions in particular. In the fall of 2014, for example, the report of the Independent Expert Advisory Group (IEAG) on the Data Revolution for Sustainable Development called for a “special investment to increase global data literacy”. The Workshop, organized at the 70th Session of the United Nations General Assembly, aims to bring together key actors from the Data Revolution community to examine the main assumptions, implication, limitations and expansions of the ‘Data Literacy’ discourse—with a focus on ways in which data can serve to engage and empower communities. The workshop’s format and content—a 2-hour off-the record informal workshop—is meant to generate in-depth and lively debates, and serve as a catalyst for future collaborations and impact. \n\nThe event will mark the launch of a White Paper “Beyond Data Literacy: Reinventing Community Engagement and Empowerment in the Age of Data” jointly developed by Data-Pop Alliance and Internews’ Center for Innovation & Learning with co-authors from the MIT Center for Civic Media. \n\nInvite only. \";s:8:\"location\";s:72:\"ThoughtWorks, Inc., 99 Madison Avenue, New York, NY 10016, United States\";s:10:\"start_time\";i:1443526200;s:8:\"end_time\";i:1443535200;s:4:\"link\";s:160:\"https://www.google.com/calendar/event?eid=XzYwczM2YzFuNjBwajhiOWk2Z3M0NmI5azZvcGphYjlwNmdzMzRiOWw2OHFqNmc5azZ0MWthaDloOGcgNmgzczUwa2IxaGZzcXVmZGx1c2pyZWJuNG9AZw\";s:8:\"day_type\";s:3:\"SPD\";}i:4;O:9:\"GCE_Event\":9:{s:4:\"feed\";r:3;s:2:\"id\";s:26:\"i275gimauch5ns0nmvd7ftlo3o\";s:5:\"title\";s:79:\"Strengthening Capacity in Developing Countries: It&#039;s time to get it right!\";s:11:\"description\";s:2475:\"Please join us for the side event:\n\nStrengthening Capacity in Developing Countries: It’s time to get it right! \n\nIn partnership with Paris21, Data-Pop Alliance will be co-hosting the event, Strengthening Capacity in Developing Countries: It\'s Time to get it Right!, alongside the United Nations General Assembly this month.\n\nThis is a vital moment for development data and statistics. The agreed upon Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) will put unprecedented pressure on developing countries to produce more and better data for monitoring, reporting and decision making.\n\nYet many developing countries are simply not ready. Despite some progress over the last 15 years, they still struggle to provide the most basic data. New ideas and practices are needed to produce responsive statistical systems with the capacity to track progress across the SDGs’ broad spectrum of development processes and outcomes.\n\nFortunately, there are already many successful experiences of statistical capacity building to learn from – as well as examples of what has not worked so well. Please join us and thought leaders from government, international organisations and civil society as they take stock of best practices over the last 15 years, discuss the potential of the new Global Partnership on Sustainable Development Data and explore bold innovations in statistical capacity building.\n\nThis event will be divided into two sessions with an aim of addressing how to strengthen capacity in developing countries around two themes: Revisiting Capacity Building and Innovation and Modernisation\n \n\nJohannes Jutting, Manager of PARIS21 and John Pullinger, Chair of the UN Statistical Commission, will open up the debate among a panel of experts including:\n\n· Shaida Badiee, Managing Director, Open Data Watch\n\n· Minister Arsenio Balisacan, Socioeconomic Planning Secretary of the Republic of the Philippines\n\n· Martine Durand, Chief Statistician and Director of the Statistics Directorate, OECD\n\n· David Hallam, Director and UK Envoy for the Post-2015 Development Goals, DFID\n\n· Emmanuel Letouzé, Director and Co-Founder, Data-Pop Alliance\n\n· Diana Nova, National Administrative Department of Statistics (DANE), Colombia\n\n· Stefan Schweinfest, Director, United Nations Statistics Division\n\n \nPlease RSVP before Wednesday 23 September by sending an email to Celia.VALEANI@oecd.org\n\nFor more information on the event: http://www.paris21.org/sites/default/files/UNGA-Side-event.pdf\";s:8:\"location\";s:68:\"The Roosevelt Hotel, 45 E 45th St, New York, NY 10017, United States\";s:10:\"start_time\";i:1443258000;s:8:\"end_time\";i:1443268800;s:4:\"link\";s:116:\"https://www.google.com/calendar/event?eid=aTI3NWdpbWF1Y2g1bnMwbm12ZDdmdGxvM28gNmgzczUwa2IxaGZzcXVmZGx1c2pyZWJuNG9AZw\";s:8:\"day_type\";s:3:\"SPD\";}}s:17:\"\0GCE_Feed\0api_key\";s:39:\"AIzaSyAssdKVved1mPVY0UJCrx96OUOF9u17AuY\";}s:2:\"id\";s:59:\"_6134cca370oj6b9m84rjab9k8h332b9o65246ba46op3ccq688r44c1g6g\";s:5:\"title\";s:34:\"Amsterdam Privacy Conference 2015 \";s:11:\"description\";s:875:\"APC 2015 brings together researchers, practitioners, policy makers and professionals in the field of privacy to share insights, exchange ideas and formulate, discuss and answer the challenging privacy questions that lie ahead of us. APC 2015 is organised by the Amsterdam Platform for Privacy Research (APPR), a network of researchers of the University of Amsterdam, with active participants from diverse fields including philosophy, law, economics, computer science, medicine, media and communication studies and social sciences. \n\n<strong><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://datapopalliance.org/people#bio-letouze\">Emmanuel Letouzé</a> will participate in the panel \"Group Privacy: the Challenge of New Technologies\". Location and exact time and date TBA.</strong>\n\nMore information about the conference can be found <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.apc2015.net/\">here</a>.\";s:8:\"location\";s:22:\"Amsterdam, Netherlands\";s:10:\"start_time\";i:1445558400;s:8:\"end_time\";i:1445904000;s:4:\"link\";s:160:\"https://www.google.com/calendar/event?eid=XzYxMzRjY2EzNzBvajZiOW04NHJqYWI5azhoMzMyYjlvNjUyNDZiYTQ2b3AzY2NxNjg4cjQ0YzFnNmcgNmgzczUwa2IxaGZzcXVmZGx1c2pyZWJuNG9AZw\";s:8:\"day_type\";s:3:\"MWD\";}i:1;r:20;i:2;r:30;i:3;r:40;i:4;r:50;}','no');
